{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17628133","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17628133"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T16:54:27+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T16:54:27+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17190"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17190","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17190"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.75,0,0.1,0.05,0.1]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9880"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"69298"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9880","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9880"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17190"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"54751"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4940"},{"type":"tags","id":"4945"},{"type":"tags","id":"10697"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"23194"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23198"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"69298","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/69298"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe structure of deoxyribonucleic acid (DNA) is fundamental to its role in storing and transmitting genetic information.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the structural arrangement of DNA?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Antiparallel strands with sugar-phosphate backbone outside","Antiparallel strands with adenine pairing with guanine","Parallel strands with bases on the outside","Parallel strands with random base pairing","Antiparallel strands with thymine pairing with cytosine"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe correct structure of DNA involves \u003Cstrong\u003Eantiparallel strands with the sugar-phosphate backbone on the outside\u003C/strong\u003E. The two strands run in opposite directions (3\u0027 to 5\u0027 and 5\u0027 to 3\u0027), with the negatively charged sugar-phosphate backbone forming the exterior of the double helix. The nitrogenous bases point inward and form specific base pairs held together by hydrogen bonds.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis structure allows for stable storage of genetic information while permitting processes such as replication and transcription. The specific base pairing (A-T and G-C) ensures accurate transmission of genetic information.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAntiparallel strands with adenine pairing with guanine\u003C/strong\u003E - Adenine pairs with thymine, not guanine\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EParallel strands with bases on the outside\u003C/strong\u003E - DNA strands are antiparallel, not parallel, and bases are internal, not external\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EParallel strands with random base pairing\u003C/strong\u003E - DNA strands are antiparallel and base pairing is specific (adenine with thymine, guanine with cytosine)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAntiparallel strands with thymine pairing with cytosine\u003C/strong\u003E - Thymine pairs with adenine, not cytosine\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["DNA double helix structure consists of two antiparallel strands connected by complementary base pairs.","Adenine pairs with thymine via two hydrogen bonds, while guanine pairs with cytosine via three hydrogen bonds.","The sugar-phosphate backbone is on the outside of the double helix while the base pairs are on the inside."],"references":["Turnpenny PD, Ellard S. Emery\u0027s Elements of Medical Genetics E-Book: Elsevier Health Sciences; 2011","Bruce Alberts, Alexander Johnson, Julian Lewis, Martin Raff, Keith Roberts, and Peter Walter, The Structure and Function of DNA, https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK26821/, 2002"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"54751"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17190"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"54751","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/54751"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-11T18:41:22+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-11T18:43:09+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9880"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"69298"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGr